{"id": "duc04-testb-7:10#31", "contents": "The president insists that the money be spent to hire 100,000 teachers across the country so that the average class can be reduced to 18 students. Republicans, railing against \"Beltway bureaucrats,\" say that local school districts should decide how the money is spent, whether it be for teachers or computers. White House chief of staff Erskine Bowles, the president's top negotiator, emerged from the session saying: \"We don't have a deal. We made some good progress. The biggest issue, still, is the 100,000 teachers.\" He added: \"There are still some open issues\" upon which no agreement has been reached, but he sounded optimistic about a session scheduled for Wednesday morning."}
